\begin_layout Section*
Research Questions and Hypotheses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primary focus of this study is to test alternative designs for improving
 the effectiveness and inclusiveness of agricultural extension services.
 We examine the relative importance of three design features: (i) the way
 the information is delivered through ICT channels, (ii) the gender composition
 of the messenger(s), and (iii) the gender composition of the viewer(s)
 in encouraging the uptake and adoption of modern input use and improved
 crop management practices.
 Specific emphasis is placed on exploring both the effectiveness and inclusivity
 of this ICT-enabled approach to extension information delivery for several
 reasons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we aim to contribute to the literature on how ICTs can incresae the
 uptake of improved management practices among smallholder farmers—a topic
 that has received considerable attention in recent years but has lacked
 sufficient evidence on which approaches work and for whom 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1111/agec.12314"

\end_inset

.
 The role of ICTs in improving access to information on crop management—as
 compared to improving access to market and price information—is a particularly
 challenging topic.
 Information of this kind is often non-excludable and non-rival in nature,
 requiring government intervention when it is under-supplied by the private
 sector.
 Government intervention typically takes the form of information campaigns,
 extension programs, and advisory services, many of which have been met
 with mixed success 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Feder2010,doi:10.1080/13892240903309595,doi:10.1080/13892249985300061,davis2008extension"

\end_inset

.
 These ambiguous outcomes are often associated with specificities of the
 technology, practice, or principle being promoted; the agroecological and
 socioeconomic context in which it is being promoted; and other confounding
 factors that may be poorly understood or too costly to address in program
 design and implementation..
 As a result, ICT applications to extension such as SMS reminders, purpose-built
 smartphone apps, portable tablets and projectors, and other hardware and
 software solutions have received considerable attention in recent years
 as a means of addressing many of these issues.
 Several studies have reported positive impacts of ICTs when applied to
 extension services.
 For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:hbs:wpaper:13-047"

\end_inset

 found that SMSs pushed to farmers in Gujarat, India generated positive
 effects on crop choice and pesticide-use decision, and that the introduction
 of an IVR system significantly increased cumin and cotton yields.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1080/00220388.2016.1146700"

\end_inset

 found that a multi-media mobile phone-based product linked to expert advisory
 services increased farmers' awareness and knowledge about specific solutions
 to their production constraints in Madhya Pradesh, India.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "maredia2017can"

\end_inset

, on the other hand, found that while mobile phone-based animated videos
 shown to farmers in Burkina Faso induced learning and understanding, it
 was no more effective in encouraging adoption than conventional approaches
 to information provision.
 In Uganda—the site of our study—Grameen Foundation had some success using
 smartphones to provide agriculture-related information to farmers through
 ICT-empowered community knowledge workers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1080/1369118X.2016.1200644"

\end_inset

, while others have shown successful pilots with both short videos 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1146/annurev-resource-100913-012714"

\end_inset

 and mobile-phone hotlines for farmers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RePEc:hbs:wpaper:13-047"

\end_inset

.
 However, it remains to be seen how far these effects can be generalized,
 and questions about cost-effectiveness, scalability, and accountability
 often remain unaddressed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, we aim to address the issue of gender bias in the provision of agricultu
ral extension services and the dissemination of information to smallholder
 farmers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doss200127,FLETSCHNER20111422,peterman2011understanding,QUISUMBING2010581"

\end_inset

.
 Often, extension agents are male, and their default strategy for disseminating
 information is to target who they assume to be the main (or most accessible)
 decision-maker in a household, which is generally the man.
 HOwever, their underlying assumption that extension messages targeting
 one household member will spread to other household members—including women
 and youth who often play a substantial role in agriculture—may be false
 in many contexts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RePEc:fpr:ifprid:1411"

\end_inset

.
 Men do not necessarily discuss production decisions or share information
 to women household members, especially if extension messages focus on men's
 priorities and crops 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "fletschner2011gender"

\end_inset

.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kabunga2012heterogeneous"

\end_inset

 find that female farmers are less likely to adopt tissue-culture banana
 technology in Kenya, but would have an equal chance to adopt the technology
 were they able to acquire sufficient information about it.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1093/erae/jbv039"

\end_inset

 investigate the effect of gendered approaches to extension training among
 farmers in South Kivu, DR Congo, and find that joint male and female participat
ion leads to the highest adoption rates for several key technologies and
 practices.
 Mechanisms that explain these effects focus largely on changes in relative
 bargaining power of the actors, gender-linked differences in access to
 complementary inputs, and overall intensity of exposure to information
 and training (see, e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Doss200127"

\end_inset

).
 Thus, evidence suggests that in certain contexts, gender homophily effects—in
 which men learn more from other men and women learn more from other women—may
 dominate other intra-household information-sharing effects 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doss200127"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third, we explore the gender dimensions of crop production by investigating
 the extent to which farms are managed at the household level in a cooperative
 manner, e.g., through joint decision-making between and among male and female
 co-heads of household.
 We test whether bringing the messages as a couple or as a female leads
 to better outcomes than when the information is given by a man as would
 be the default case.
 We base this exploration on the assumption that social norms prevent women
 from playing a more prominent role in household agriculture.
 Gender stereotyping, where women are expected to tend to small gardens
 used to produce for home consumption and men are responsible for cash crops
 using inputs obtained from the market, may contribute to inefficient allocation
 of resources within the household as a single unit of production.
 This expands on recent research on how information campaigns can be used
 to change beliefs, norms, and perceptions—work that has been ongoing in
 public health and has only recently started to trickle through to other
 disciplines.
 It also expands on recent advances in the measurement of gendered dimensions
 of empowerment in agricultural households, including decison-making power,
 intra-household distribution of decision-making power and control over
 income and resources 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ALKIRE201371,MAHMUD2012610"

\end_inset

.
 We add to this body of work by specifically examining if women's involvement
 in maize farming can be increased by questioning cultural norms and influencing
 aspirations though ICT-enabled extension 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RePEc:smu:ecowpa:1705,riley"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally and more broadly, we contribute to long-standing research efforts
 to document and measure the adoption and impact of improved agricultural
 technologies and management practices among smallholder farmers.
 There are many reasons for the observed low rates of adoption of improved
 technologies and practices among smallholder farmers, including lack of
 access to credit and insurance, poorly developed labour markets, and asymmetrie
s of information 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1086/451461,jack2013market"

\end_inset

.
 Our contribution is methodological in nature in recognition of two important
 points.
 First, too few studies apply sufficiently rigorous methods to address concerns
 about sample selection bias and causal identification in the study of technical
 change in developing-country agriculture 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "de2010recent"

\end_inset

.
 Second, too few studies on ICT-enabled extension are replicated in differing
 contexts and populations to increase both generalizable findings and nuanced
 insights on the impact pathways through which ICT operates on farmers'
 decision-making about technology adoption.
 Our study adds to this growing body of literature by adapting a design
 tha is similar to work in progress in Ethiopia 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "tanguydiggreen"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our experimental design (described in detail below) allows us to explore
 these research questions by comparing outcomes between groups of randomly
 assigned farmers that are given the opportunity to view versions of a video
 on improved maize management practices in different configurations.
 In addition to the video, a random group of farmers also received a phone
 number and instructions to call into the IVR system.
 A final random subset of these farmers were also targeted by eight SMS
 messages reminding them at specific times about the application and use
 of important practices, and the fact that they can always call the IRV
 for additional information.
 The experiment allows us to test the following three hypotheses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
H1: Improving the provision of information to smallholder farmers results
 in increases in awareness and knowledge about improved technologies and
 practices, increases in the adoption of these technologies and practices,
 improvements in on-farm productivity gains, and improvements in household
 welfare.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
H2: The effectiveness of information depends on who is targeted: jointly
 to male and female co-heads in a household or only the female co-head in
 the household as opposed to only to the male co-head.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
H3: The effectiveness of information depends on who brings the information:
 jointly by male and female co-heads in a household or only the female co-head
 in the household as opposed to only the the male co-head.
\end_layout

